<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-032-343 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 406 215</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Oct 16 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ITC rules in Texas Instrument's favor on patent claims.andO;(International Trade Commission)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCormick, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Texas Instruments Inc. (Cases).andO;Topic:     PatentLegal IssuesCourt CasesGovernment AgencySemiconductor industryMicroprocessorsUnited States. International Trade Commission.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>****ITC Rules In Texas Instrument's Favor On Patent Claims 10/16/91WASHINGTON, DC, U.S.A., 1991 OCT 16 (NB) -- The International TradeCommission (U.S.andP;  Department of Commerce) has issued a preliminary rulingthat says five U.S.andP;  companies are infringing on a basic semiconductor patentwhich was issued to Texas Instruments.andM;The patent in question covers a special packaging process used worldwide bymost semiconductor manufacturers and in particular by Analog Devices, CypressSemiconductor Corporation, Integrated Device Technology, LSI Logic, and VLSITechnology.andM;The bottom-gating packaging process involves the way plastic is flowed intothe mold cavity around the semiconductor chip and its associated connectingpins.andM;In a ruling on an ITC complaint filed back in 1986 by Texas Instruments,Korean and Japanese companies were earlier found in violation of this sameU.S.andP;  Patent #4,043,027, &quot;Process for Encapsulating Electronic Components inPlastic,&quot; awarded to TI in 1977.andM;This packaging system was developed nearly 30 years ago by TI and was onemajor factor in making inexpensive semiconductors available in massquantities.andM;This preliminary ruling by Administrative Law Judge Sidney Harris now goes tothe full ITC for review before taking effect.andP;  Presidential approval is alsorequired, but if the ruling goes into force the five companies would beforced to stop making or importing chips made using this technique or theywould have to license the technology from TI.andM;Another important packaging method, called top-gating, was ruled by the judgeto not come under the TI patent.andM;(John McCormick/19911016)</TEXT></DOC>